= Introduction

Are you looking to convert your header-based C{plus}{plus} codebase to
C{plus}{plus}20 modules, but afraid that modularizing is too cumbersome?
*importizer* is here to help.

And by modularization I don't mean exposing a module interface and wrapping.
headers. I mean native modules a.k.a using modules internally.

*Note:* This project is currently going through a complete rewrite using
Clang LibTooling to replace Regex (pre-2.0.0). Much pre-2.0.0 things are
gone, but releases and git history are still preserved.

This project uses https://semver.org[semantic versioning].

== Why Native C{plus}{plus} Modules?

* *Improved compilation time:* Modules don’t need to be recompiled every
time it is imported, unlike headers.
* *Improved encapsulation:* Modules allow you to choose what is exposed
to users (exported), no need to hide stuff with a `detail` namespace.
Includes and macros from a module will only stay in that module.
* https://arewemodulesyet.org

= Prebuilt Executable

* Select your operating system:
** Windows (10{plus} only)
** MacOS (14{plus} only)
** Linux (glibc 2.35{plus} only)
* Download the *debug* versions (with sanitizers and no optimizations)
from the
https://github.com/msqr1/importizer/releases/tag/continuous[continuous
tag].
* For production use, download the *release* versions (with
optimizations) from the other releases.

= Options

* Importizer uses a TOML configuration file to control its behavior. By
default, it looks for `importizer.toml` in the current working directory
but you can also provide a path to one with `importizer [config path]`. All
relative paths in config file are relative to it, not CWD.

[%autowidth.stretch]
|===
|CLI option|Description
|-h, --help|Print help (basically this section) and exit
|-v, --version|Print version and exit
|-o, --outDir|Output directory (will override config file)
|===

[%autowidth.stretch]
|===
|Config file option|Description|Type
|inDir|Input directory (required)|String
|outDir|Output directory (required if not on CLI)|String
|compilationDb|JSON compilation database (highly recommended)|String
|===

For projects without a compilation database, importizer supports them by trying
to imitate one via the following set of settings called 'bootstrap'.
These can be specified `bootstrap` table in config file.

[%autowidth.stretch]
|===
|Bootstrap option|Description|Default values|Type
|hdrExts|Header file extensions used in the project|`["h","hh","hpp","hxx",""]`|String array
|srcExts|Source file extensions used in the project|`["cc","cpp","cxx","c++","C"]`|String array
|includePaths|Include paths to search|`[]`|String array
|===

= Developing

== Building from Source

[source,bash]
----
git clone --depth 1 https://github.com/msqr1/importizer &&
cd importizer &&
cmake -B build -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release &&
cmake --build build --config Release -j $(cmake -P ../scripts/Nproc.cmake)
----

* The executable `importizer` will be located in `build`

== Executable-dependencies information

[%autowidth.stretch]
|===
| |Linux |MacOS |Windows
|LibTooling |Dynamic^1^ |Dynamic^1^ |Dynamic^1^

|LLVM |Dynamic^1^ |Dynamic^1^ |Dynamic^1^

|LibC |Dynamic^4^ |Dynamic^2^ |Dynamic^3^

|LibC{plus}{plus} |Static |Dynamic^2^ |Static

|Other 3rd-party |Static |Static |Static

|Distributed as |tgz(Executable {plus} .so) |tgz(Executable {plus}
.dylib) |zip(Executable {plus} .dll)
|===

[arabic]
. Package manager doesn’t offer static version, pending self-built LLVM
. Dynamic with stable ABI guaranteed by macOS (libSystem), we can treat
as if static
. Dynamic with stable ABI guaranteed by Windows (UCRT), we can treat as
if static
. Dynamic glibc, pending switch to musl

== Testing

* Add `-DBUILD++_++TESTING=1` when configuring CMake.
* Build, then `cd ++[++build root++]++/src/test`.
* Run `ctest`. Test outputs is in `test-outs`
* If possible, file an issue for test(s) that failed.

== Contribution rules

* Use camelCase for C{plus}{plus} & CMake variables and functions
* Use PascalCase for C{plus}{plus} classes, types, and all files (except for the special ones)
* Use kebab-case for executables and directories
* Use ALL++_++CAPS++_++SNAKE++_++CASE for CMake external variables
* Follow LLVM coding style
* Keep the maximum line width around 90 columns.
* Maintain consistent ordering of options in the README, `struct Opts`,
and value-checking logic.
* Always name the C++ file with `main()` "Driver"
* Linking order: `common-config` --> importizer's --> 3rd-party
* Files to update version for new release:
** .github/workflows/release.yml
** src/Opts.cc
** CMakeLists.txt
** ChangeLog.md
